Miffed and confused, I resent it in, and when I went to vote today, I was not on the rolls. I asked for a provisional ballot and got one, but in a state notorious for voter suppression, in an area that generally votes liberal, it is suspect at best.
It told me that the last four of my social security number I had registered with was wrong. Except it wasn't. The last four is the same four I've always used, and the numbers they had were right.

Frustrated that they didn't just...register me but say I couldn't mail in...I re-registered in August, long before the registration deadline of October 5. Then, on October 16, two full months after my registration and 10 days past the deadline, I received another correspondence.

In May, I moved to Austin. I immediately applied to register as a mail-in voter, not knowing that Texas doesn't let you unless you're 65+ or disabled. I sent it in, and 6 weeks later got mail saying I couldn't, but also, that my registration was thrown out entirely because of it.

RT @wiredunion: Since its founding 27 years ago, WIRED has prepared readers and viewers for the promises and upheavals of the future. Now i‚Ä¶

I look forward to what the future holds for all of us, I look forward to continuing to share and cover the story of our lifetimes with you all, and I hope you join us in supporting something that I think will make sure we get to for a very, very long time.

Personally, I know I come from a place of privilege‚Äîin this job, in how I was raised, and what I was born with. For me I believe every time you have a chance to raise the floor for others, especially for those more vulnerable than you, it is not just right, it is your duty.

I've never been more proud to work at WIRED than during this pandemic. Our coverage has never been so important, and that's why it's more critical than ever that we keep this thing going, and ensure we can keep covering, sharing, and designing the stories you read every day.

And I'm not alone. 85% of the eligible workers at WIRED have joined, and we follow in the footsteps of our sister brand, @newyorkerunion, who has supported us all the way, and who Conde Nast voluntarily recognized and bargains with today.

My job at WIRED is the best job I've had in my life, at the best company I've worked for in my life. And in times like these that are so uncertain, it is more important than ever to work together, to be heard, to get a window into the rooms that govern our livelihoods.

I love my manager. I love my Editor in Chief. I love WIRED. And that's exactly why I'm doing this. To support my coworkers and this place I love, and to have a seat at that table. This isn't about money, but about equality. It's not about poor treatment, but about transparency.

In global pandemics, we‚Äôre all in it together. Every bar of soap, every roll of toilet paper, every bottle of medicine you take is one someone else can‚Äôt have. Every restaurant and bar you enter raises the chances, even if just a little, that you or someone else will die.
